In [68]:
k_range = range(1, 10)
scores = []
for k in k_range:
    knn = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=k)
    scores.append(np.mean(cross_val_score(knn, X, y, cv=10, scoring='accuracy')))

# plot the K values (x-axis) versus the 10-fold CV score (y-axis)
plt.figure()
plt.plot(k_range, scores)
plt.xlabel('k value')
plt.ylabel('accuracy')
Out[68]:

from sklearn.grid_search import GridSearchCV

knn = KNeighborsClassifier()
k_range = range(1, 10)
param_grid = dict(n_neighbors=k_range)
grid = GridSearchCV(knn, param_grid, cv=10, scoring='accuracy')
grid.fit(X, y)

# check the results of the grid search
grid.grid_scores_
grid_mean_scores = [result[1] for result in grid.grid_scores_]
plt.figure()
plt.plot(k_range, grid_mean_scores)
plt.show()

Employee satisfaction, salary, and monthly always were all highly correlated to an employee leaving or quitting a company. Employee satisfication had the highest correlation with every singal model. B) Based on this research, HR Departments are able to learn from the findings and implement programs that keep people at the company. By focusing on programs and creating an environment that keeps employee satisfaction high will ensure that the company goes through less turnover. HR departments can also implement hour caps to make sure that employees aren't being overworked. They can also use this research to determine if they are paying their employees enough. If not they can raise wages if needed to be more competitive¶

C) Having additional data is always important to improving classification models because we are able to get a more complete "picture" of what is going on.
